Clone a Repository
bash
Copy code
git clone <repository_url>
Example:

bash
Copy code
git clone https://github.com/user/repo.git
Clones the repository from the given URL to your local machine.

Commit Changes
bash
Copy code
git add <file>
git commit -m "Commit message"
Example:

bash
Copy code
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
Adds all changes to the staging area and commits them with a message.

Push Changes
bash
Copy code
git push origin <branch>
Example:

bash
Copy code
git push origin main
Pushes your committed changes to the remote repository on the specified branch.

Fetch Updates
bash
Copy code
git fetch
Fetches updates from the remote repository but does not merge them into your local branch.

Pull Updates
bash
Copy code
git pull
Fetches and merges updates from the remote repository into your current branch.

Checkout a Branch
bash
Copy code
git checkout <branch>
Example:

bash
Copy code
git checkout feature-branch
Switches to the specified branch.

Reset Changes
bash
Copy code
git reset <file>
git reset --hard
Example:

bash
Copy code
git reset README.md
git reset --hard
The first command unstages a file, the second command resets the entire working directory to the last commit.

Delete a Branch
bash
Copy code
git branch -d <branch>
git push origin --delete <branch>
Example:

bash
Copy code
git branch -d feature-branch
git push origin --delete feature-branch
The first command deletes a local branch, and the second command deletes a remote branch.

Show Process of Each Command
Clone a Repository:

Navigate to the directory where you want to clone the repository.
Run the git clone command with the repository URL.
Commit Changes:

Make changes to your files.
Add the changes to the staging area with git add.
Commit the changes with a descriptive message using git commit.
Push Changes:

Ensure you are on the correct branch.
Push your committed changes to the remote repository with git push.
Fetch Updates:

Run git fetch to see what others have committed without merging the changes into your branch.
Pull Updates:

Run git pull to fetch and merge updates from the remote repository.
Checkout a Branch:

List available branches with git branch.
Switch to the desired branch using git checkout.
Reset Changes:

Unstage specific files with git reset <file>.
Discard all local changes with git reset --hard.
Delete a Branch:

Delete a local branch with git branch -d.
Delete a remote branch with git push origin --delete.
Each of these commands helps manage different aspects of version control in a Git repository, facilitating collaboration and efficient workflow management.






